Until the late 1900s, the black-capped chickadee was considered by some to be conspecific with the [[willow tit]] of Eurasia and the Carolina chickadee, due to their very similar appearance.<ref name=Smith1991/>{{rp|8–9}} A 1989 study demonstrated that the Willow tit and black-capped chickadee were different species;<ref name="Gill1989">{{cite journal |last1=Gill |first1=Frank B. |last2=Funk |first2=David H. |last3=Silverin |first3=Bengt |title=Protein Relationships among Titmice (''Parus'') |journal=The Wilson Bulletin |date=1989 |volume=101 |issue=2 |pages=182–197 |jstor=4162724 }}</ref> however, the distinction of the Carolina chickadee remained in question until 2005.<ref name=Gill2005/>

===Subspecies===
Nine subspecies are currently recognized. They are presented below in the taxonomic order set by the [[International Ornithologists' Union]] (IOC)<ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | year=2018 | title=Waxwings and allies, tits, penduline tits | work=World Bird List Version 14.1 | url=http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/waxwings/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union | access-date=17 January 2024 }}</ref>
*''Poecile atricapillus turneri'' <small>([[Robert Ridgway|Ridgway]], 1884)</small>: Found in southern Alaska and northwest Canada and has the palest colouring of all subspecies.<ref name=ioc/><ref name=FooteBotW>{{cite journal |last1=Foote |first1=Jennifer R. |last2=Mennill |first2=Daniel J. |last3=Ratcliffe |first3=Laurene M. |last4=Smith |first4=Susan M. |editor-first1=Alan F. |editor-last1=Poole |title=Black-capped Chickadee (''Poecile atricapillus'') |journal=Birds of the World |date=4 March 2020 |doi=10.2173/bow.bkcchi.01 |s2cid=85228007 |access-date=17 January 2024 |url=https://birdsoftheworld.org/bow/species/bkcchi/cur/introduction |url-access=subscription }}</ref>
*''Poecile atricapillus occidentalis'' <small>([[Spencer Fullerton Baird|Baird]], 1858)</small>: Ranges from southwest British Columbia to northwest California, and is the smallest in size and darkest in colouring of all subspecies.<ref name=ioc/><ref name=FooteBotW/>
*''Poecile atricapillus fortuitus'' <small>([[William Leon Dawson|Dawson]], 1909)</small>: Ranges from inland southwest Canada to northwest U.S., and is notably buffier than other subspecies.<ref name=ioc/><ref name=Smith1991/>{{rp|16}}
*''Poecile atricapillus septentrionalis'' <small>([[Edward Harris (ornithologist)|Harris]], 1846)</small>: Ranges from western and central Canada to southern U.S. It is visually similar to ''P.&nbsp;a. atricapillus'' but has slightly longer wings and tail.<ref name=ioc/><ref name=FooteBotW/>
*''Poecile atricapillus bartletti'' <small>([[John Warren Aldrich|Alrich]] & Nutt, 1939)</small>: Lives only in [[Newfoundland]], Canada, and is the only species with different mtDNA, likely due to geographic isolation.<ref name=ioc/><ref name=FooteBotW/> It is larger and darker than ''P.&nbsp;a. atricapillus''.<ref name=Smith1991/>{{rp|15}}
*''Poecile atricapillus atricapillus'' <small>(Linnaeus, 1766)</small>: [[Nominate subspecies]], which ranges from eastern and central Canada to northeastern U.S.<ref name=ioc/>
*''Poecile atricapillus garrinus'' <small>([[William H. Behle|Behle]], 1951)</small>: Lives in western central U.S.<ref name=ioc/> It has a brown back and buff rump.<ref name=Smith1991/>{{rp|16}}
*''Poecile atricapillus nevadensis'' <small>(Linsdale, 1938)</small>: Lives in western U.S., and is visually similar to ''P.&nbsp;a. septentrionalis'' but with paler edges to the wings and tail.<ref name=ioc/><ref name=Smith1991/>{{rp|16}}
*''Poecile atricapillus practicus'' <small>([[Harry C. Oberholser|Oberholser]], 1937)</small>: Lives in the [[Appalachian Mountains]] in the eastern U.S.<ref name=ioc/> Similar to ''P.&nbsp;a. atricapillus'', although slightly smaller, less dark on the back, and less prominent white edge to the wings and tail.<ref name=Smith1991/>{{rp|14}}

==Description==
[[File:Black-capped Chickadee Stratham NH, Aug 2013.jpg|thumb|left|Black-capped chickadee clinging to a wire]] 
The black-capped chickadee has a black cap and "bib" with white cheeks. Its underparts are white with buff-coloured flanks. Its back is unstreaked and greenish grey, and the tail and wings are slate grey. It has a black [[beak]] and legs, and dark brown [[iris (anatomy)|irises]]. Males and females are generally similar, although males have a larger bib. They can also be distinguished based on a combination of weight and tail length. [[Bird feet and legs|Tarsus]] length does not significantly differentiate sexes.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Desrochers |first=André |date=Winter 1990 |title=Sex Determination of Black-Capped Chickadees with a Discriminant Analysis |url=https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/jfo/v061n01/p0079-p0084.pdf |journal=Journal of Field Ornithology |volume=61 |issue=1 |pages=79–84 |via=Searchable Ornithological Research Archive}}</ref> Males have a wing length of {{cvt|63.5-67.5|mm|in}}, a tail length of {{cvt|58-63|mm|in}}, a bill length of {{cvt|8-9.5|mm|in}}, and a tarsus length of {{cvt|16-17|mm|in}}. Females are on average slightly smaller, with a wing length of {{cvt|60.5-66.5|mm|in}}, a tail length of {{cvt|56.3-63|mm|in}}, a bill length of {{cvt|9-9.5|mm|in}}, and a tarsus length of {{convert|16-17|mm|in|abbr=on}}. Both sexes weigh {{cvt|10-14|g|oz}}.<ref name=FooteBotW/> Juveniles are visually similar to adults but with fluffier [[plumage]].<ref name=Smith1991/>{{rp|5}}

Although range can generally be used to separate them, the black-capped chickadee is very similar in appearance to the [[Carolina chickadee]]. The edges of the wings are somewhat paler than the Carolina chickadee, and the bib of the black-capped chickadee has a "messier" border than the Carolina chickadee. The most reliable way to distinguish the two species is by vocalizations. Black-capped chickadees have a slower, hoarser, two-part song, whereas Carolina chickadees have a three-part song.<ref name=FooteBotW/>

Black-capped chickadees are also somewhat similar to [[mountain chickadee]]s and [[boreal chickadee]]s. Mountain chickadees can be distinguished by a distinct white stripe above their eyes, and boreal chickadees have a brown cap as opposed to the black cap of the black-capped chickadee.<ref name="AAB">{{cite web |title=Black-capped Chickadee – Similar Species Comparison |url=https://www.allaboutbirds.org/guide/Black-capped_Chickadee/species-compare/ |website=[[Cornell Lab of Ornithology|All About Birds]] |publisher=Cornell University |access-date=18 January 2024}}</ref>

===Vocalization===
[[File:Chickadee - natures pics.jpg|thumb|Black-capped chickadee, Iona Beach Regional Park]]

The vocalizations of the black-capped chickadee are highly complex, with 16 distinct types of vocalizations being used to convey an array of information.<ref name="Smith1991">{{cite book |last1=Smith |first1=Susan M. |title=The black capped Chickadee: behavioral ecology and natural history |date=1991 |publisher=Comstock Publ. Assoc |location=Ithaca, NY |isbn=0-8014-2382-1}}</ref> These vocalizations are likely an evolutionary adaptation to their habitat; they live and feed in dense vegetation, and even when the flock is close together, individual birds tend to be out of each other's visual range.<ref name=Ficken>{{cite journal |last1=Ficken |first1=M. S. |last2=Ficken |first2=R. W. |last3=Witkin |first3=S. R. |year=1978 |title=Vocal repertoire of the Black-capped Chickadee |journal=[[Auk (journal)|Auk]] |volume=95 |issue=1 |pages=34–48 |url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/auk/v095n01/p0034-p0048.pdf |doi=10.2307/4085493|jstor=4085493 }}</ref>

One of the most recognizable sounds produced, particularly by the males, is the two-note ''fee-bee'' song. It is a simple, clear whistle of two notes, identical in rhythm, the first roughly a [[Major second|whole-step]] above the second.<ref name="WholeStep">{{cite web |last=Jackson |first=Dave |title=Olympic Peninsula Audubon Society |publisher=Olympic Peninsula Audubon Society |date=24 March 2010 |url=http://www.olympicpeninsulaaudubon.org/shell.php?page=gazette_Mar_2010 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130415150534/http://www.olympicpeninsulaaudubon.org/shell.php?page=gazette_Mar_2010 |archive-date=15 April 2013 |access-date=13 March 2012 }}</ref> 
The frequency of their songs typically starts around 400&nbsp;[[Hertz|Hz]], and various tones spanning roughly 1&nbsp;kHz are sung within the song. A decrease of roughly 200&nbsp;Hz occurs when the first note (''fee'') is sung, and then another decrease around 400&nbsp;Hz takes place between the end of ''fee'' and the beginning of ''bee''. In spite of these multiple changes in frequency, though, anybody listening to the song only hears a pure, high-frequency tone.<ref name="Otter207">{{cite book|last1=Otter|first1=Ken A|title=Ecology and Behaviour of Chickadees and Titmice: An Integrated Approach|date=2007|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=978-0-19-856999-2|pages=153–230}}</ref> This is distinguished from the Carolina chickadee's four-note call ''fee-bee fee-bay''; the lower notes are nearly identical but the higher ''fee'' notes are omitted, making the black-capped song like ''bee bay''. The males sing the song only in relative isolation from other chickadees (including their mates). In late summer, some young birds sing only a single note.<ref name="Allometry">{{cite journal |last1=Templeton |first1=C. N. |last2=Greene |first2=E. |last3=Davis |first3=K. |title=Allometry of alarm calls: black-capped chickadees encode information about predator size |pmid=15976305 |doi=10.1126/science.1108841 |year=2005 |journal=Science |volume=308 |issue=5730 |pages=1934–7|bibcode=2005Sci...308.1934T |s2cid=42276496 }}</ref>

