Black-capped chickadees make a number of other calls and sounds, such as a ''gargle'' noise usually used by males to indicate a threat of attacking another male, often when feeding. This call is also used in sexual contexts.<ref name="Podos2013">{{cite journal|last1=Goodwin|first1=Sarah E.|last2=Podos|first2=Jeffrey|title=Shift of song frequencies in response to masking tones|journal=Animal Behaviour|date=9 January 2013|volume=85|issue=2|pages=435–440|doi=10.1016/j.anbehav.2012.12.003|bibcode=2013AnBeh..85..435G |s2cid=53269430 }}</ref> Black-capped chickadees learn the ''gargle'' noise soon after birth and continues to develop it through to adulthood.<ref name="Otter207" /> This noise is among the most complex of the calls; in one population of chickadees, the ''gargle'' contained 2 to 9 instances of 14 distinct notes, all sung within half a second.<ref name="Podos2013" />

Social learning in particular is largely influential to the development of the ''gargle''. Beginning 30 to 35 days after birth, strings of low-amplitude precursor or sub-''gargles'' are produced for about a minute. At this time, they learn to produce such sounds by listening to their parents and siblings. Three chickadee populations were observed at three different sites over 8 years, and all of them produced vocalizations that were very similar to one another. Strings of juvenile sub-''gargles'' are almost perfectly continuous and both low and unstable in frequency, yet lacking multiple syllables. When their vocal abilities are fully developed, a stable frequency is produced and a variety of syllables is heard that vary in length.<ref name="Otter207" />

Other calls which have been noted include a "broken ''dee''", "variable ''see''", ''hiss'', ''snarl'' ''twitter'', "high ''zee''", and ''tseet''. Some of these calls are used during breeding to attract a mate or reinforce a pair bond, such as the "broken ''dee''" and "variable ''see''". Others, such as the ''snarl'' and ''twitter'', are used territorially.<ref name=Smith1991/>{{rp|57}}

Black-capped chickadees in an environment with ambient noise at the same frequencies as their songs are able to adjust the frequency of their songs to effectively communicate with the surrounding population. When interacting with other chickadees close by, the males matched their frequencies; however, when the surrounding environment was noisy with other species, the males adapted by increasing the frequency of their songs. Another survey, though, showed that male chickadees sometimes intentionally match the tones of competing chickadees as a way of showing aggression. Dominant males in a population often compete with lower-ranked males, and singing contests are a way male chickadees decide who gets to mate. When a male loses a contest, particularly a higher-ranking male in the population, he will often have difficulty finding a mate.<ref name="Podos2013" />

==Distribution and habitat==
Black-capped chickadees are [[Bird migration|non-migratory]] and can be found throughout much of North America.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Black-capped Chickadee {{!}} Audubon Field Guide |url=https://www.audubon.org/field-guide/bird/black-capped-chickadee |access-date=20 April 2024 |language=en}}</ref> They range from western Alaska, through southern Yukon and throughout the Canadian provinces, from British Columbia in the west to the [[Maritimes]] and Newfoundland in the east. The distribution continues into the United States, with its range extending to northern California in the south-west, through northern Nevada and New Mexico, continuing through the midwestern United States to New Jersey. It can also be found in the [[Appalachian Mountains]] at higher elevations.<ref name=FooteBotW/> In British Columbia, the black-capped chickadee is absent on [[Vancouver Island]], the [[Gulf Islands]], [[Haida Gwaii]], and parts of the [[Sunshine Coast (British Columbia)|Sunshine Coast]], where it is replaced by the [[chestnut-backed chickadee]].<ref name=Wright2015>{{cite web |last1=Wright |first1=K. G. |title=Black-capped Chickadee |url=https://www.birdatlas.bc.ca/accounts/speciesaccount.jsp?sp=BCCH&lang=en |publisher=The Atlas of the Breeding Birds of British Columbia |access-date=29 January 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Dahlsten |first1=Donald L. |last2=Brennan |first2=Leonard A. |last3=McCallum |first3=D. Archibald |last4=Gaunt |first4=Sandra L. |editor-first1=Alan F. |editor-first2=Frank B. |editor-last1=Poole |editor-last2=Gill |title=Chestnut-backed Chickadee (''Poecile rufescens'') |journal=Birds of the World |date=4 March 2020 |doi=10.2173/bow.chbchi.01}}</ref> They are typically most common at elevations below {{cvt|750|m|ft}},<ref name=Wright2015/> although they have been known to occur at up to {{cvt|3200|m|ft}}.<ref name="iucn status"/>

Black-capped chickadees inhabit wooded areas, including both [[Coniferous forest|coniferous]] and [[Deciduous forest|deciduous]] forests, urban parks, willow thickets, and suburban areas. They do not vary their habitat between breeding and non-breeding seasons, although in the winter irregular [[Bird migration#Irruptions and dispersal|bird migration and dispersal]] may occur.<ref name=FooteBotW/>

==Behaviour and ecology==
===Diet and foraging===
[[File:Black-capped chickadee (41417).jpg|thumb|Eating seeds in [[Central Park]]]]
[[File:Poecile atricapillus CT.ogv|right|thumb|Black-capped chickadee working on a sunflower seed, [[:en:Cap Tourmente National Wildlife Area|Cap Tourmente National Wildlife Area]], [[Quebec|Quebec, Canada]]]]
Insects (especially caterpillars) form a large part of their diet in summer. The birds hop along tree branches searching for food, sometimes hanging upside down or hovering; they may make short flights to catch insects in the air. Seeds and berries become more important in winter, though insect eggs and pupae are eaten when available.<ref name=FooteBotW/> Black-capped chickadees have also been known to eat the fat off of dead mammals.<ref name="Hammerstrom">{{cite journal |last1=Hammerstrom |first1=Frances |title=Dominance in Winter Flocks of Chickadees |journal=The Wilson Bulletin |date=1942 |volume=54 |issue=1 |pages=32–42 |url=https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/wilson/v054n01/p0032-p0042.pdf |access-date=27 January 2024}}</ref> Sunflower seeds are readily taken from bird feeders. The birds take a seed in their beak and commonly fly from the feeder to a tree, where they proceed to hammer the seed on a branch to open it.<ref name=Brittingham/>

Like many other species in the family Paridae, black-capped chickadees commonly [[Hoarding (animal behavior)|cache]] food, mostly seeds, but sometimes insects, also.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Heinrich |first1=Bernd |last2=Collins |first2=Scott L. |title=Caterpillar Leaf Damage, and the Game of Hide-and-seek with Birds |date=June 1983 |journal=Ecology |volume=64 |pages=592–602 |number=3 |doi=10.2307/1939978 |jstor=1939978|bibcode=1983Ecol...64..592H }}</ref> Items are stored singly in various sites such as bark, dead leaves, clusters of conifer needles, or knothole. Memory for the location of caches can last up to 28 days.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hitchcock |first1=C. L. |last2=Sherry |first2=D. F. |title=Long-term memory for cache sites in the Black-capped Chickadee |doi=10.1016/S0003-3472(05)80699-2 |year=1990 |journal=Animal Behaviour |volume=40 |issue=4 |page=701|bibcode=1990AnBeh..40..701H |s2cid=54417376 }}</ref> Within the first 24 hours, the birds can even remember the relative quality of the stored items.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Sherry |first=D. F. |title=Food storage by the Black-capped Chickadee: memory for the location and contents of caches |doi=10.1016/S0003-3472(84)80281-X |year=1984 |journal=Animal Behaviour |volume=32 |issue=2 |page=451|s2cid=53151283 }}</ref>

This caching behaviour has led to black-capped chickadees having larger [[Hippocampus|hippocampi]]{{refn|group=Note|The hippocampus plays a role in converting short-term memory to long-term memory, as well as supporting spatial memory.<ref name="Squire1992">{{cite journal |last1=Squire |first1=Larry R. |title=Memory and the hippocampus: A synthesis from findings with rats, monkeys, and humans. |journal=Psychological Review |date=1992 |volume=99 |issue=2 |pages=195–231 |doi=10.1037/0033-295X.99.2.195|pmid=1594723 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=O'Keefe |first1=John M. |last2=Nadel |first2=Lynn |last3=O'Keefe |first3=John |title=The hippocampus as a cognitive map |date=1978 |publisher=Clarendon Press |location=Oxford |isbn=0-19-857206-9 |url=https://www.cmor-faculty.rice.edu/~cox/neuro/HCMComplete.pdf |access-date=28 January 2024}}</ref>}} compared to other chickadees, who themselves have relatively larger hippocampi compared to other caching birds in the Paridae family.<ref name="Sherry1989">{{cite journal |last1=Sherry |first1=David F. |title=Food Storing in the Paridae |journal=The Wilson Bulletin |date=1989 |volume=101 |issue=2 |pages=289–304 |url=https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/wilson/v101n02/p0289-p0304.pdf |access-date=28 January 2024 |issn=0043-5643}}</ref><ref name="Hampton1995">{{cite journal |last1=Hampton |first1=Robert R. |last2=Sherry |first2=David F. |last3=Shettleworth |first3=Sara J. |last4=Khurgel |first4=Moshe |last5=Ivy |first5=Gwen |title=Hippocampal Volume and Food-Storing Behavior Are Related in Parids |journal=Brain, Behavior and Evolution |date=1995 |volume=45 |issue=1 |pages=54–61 |doi=10.1159/000113385|pmid=7866771 }}</ref> This variation in size also exists within the black-capped chickadee population based on the region they inhabit, with those who live in harsher climates (such as Alaska) having larger hippocampi.<ref name="Roth2009">{{cite journal |last1=Roth |first1=Timothy C |last2=Pravosudov |first2=Vladimir V |title=Hippocampal volumes and neuron numbers increase along a gradient of environmental harshness: a large-scale comparison |journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences |date=7 February 2009 |volume=276 |issue=1656 |pages=401–405 |doi=10.1098/rspb.2008.1184|pmid=18945667 |pmc=2664346 |bibcode=2009PBioS.276..401R }}</ref> However, no variation exists between the sexes.<ref name="Petersen1996">{{cite journal |last1=Petersen |first1=Karin |last2=Sherry |first2=David F. |title=No sex difference occurs in hippocampus, food-storing, or memory for food caches in black-capped chickadees |journal=Behavioural Brain Research |date=September 1996 |volume=79 |issue=1–2 |pages=15–22 |doi=10.1016/0166-4328(95)00257-X|pmid=8883812 |s2cid=4033382 }}</ref> The size of the hippocampus within black-capped chickadees also varies throughout the year, being the largest in October, and the smallest in February. While the exact reason for this seasonal change is unknown, it is believed that the hippocampus grows to allow the chickadee to remember its cache locations, and then shrinks as those caches are used up.<ref name="Smulders1995">{{cite journal |last1=Smulders |first1=T. V. |last2=Sasson |first2=A. D. |last3=DeVoogd |first3=T. J. |title=Seasonal variation in hippocampal volume in a food-storing bird, the black-capped chickadee |journal=Journal of Neurobiology |date=May 1995 |volume=27 |issue=1 |pages=15–25 |doi=10.1002/neu.480270103 |pmid=7643072 }}</ref><ref name="Phillmore2006">{{cite journal |last1=Phillmore |first1=Leslie S. |last2=Hoshooley |first2=Jennifer S. |last3=Sherry |first3=David F. |last4=MacDougall-Shackleton |first4=Scott A. |title=Annual cycle of the black-capped chickadee: Seasonality of singing rates and vocal-control brain regions |journal=Journal of Neurobiology |date=August 2006 |volume=66 |issue=9 |pages=1002–1010 |doi=10.1002/neu.20282|pmid=16779824 }}</ref>

[[File:Black-capped chickadee (33729).jpg|thumb|Black-capped chickadee at a [[Bird feeder|feeder]]]]
Foraging behaviour in the winter tends to decrease, primarily being affected by lower temperatures and stronger winds.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Otter|first1=Ken A.|title=Ecology and Behaviour of Chickadees and Titmice|date=2007|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|location=New York, NY|isbn=978-0-19-856999-2|page=268}}</ref> In parts of the black-capped chickadee's range with very cold winters, such as Minnesota, survival rates are affected by access to supplemental food. Chickadees with access to bird feeders in a very cold winter are twice as likely to survive than those without access to this supplemental food; months with severe weather when the temperature drops below {{convert|-18|C|F}} for more than five days make the primary difference between the survival rates with and without feeders.<ref name=Brittingham>{{cite journal |last1=Brittingham |first1=M.C.|last2=Temple |first2=S.A. |title=Impacts of Supplemental Feeding on Survival Rates of Black-capped Chickadees |year=1988 |journal=Ecology |volume=69 |issue=3 |page=581|doi=10.2307/1941007|jstor=1941007|bibcode=1988Ecol...69..581B }}</ref> In Pennsylvania on the southern edge of their range, with milder winters, monitoring of populations with and without feeders suggests that feeders in milder weather influence movements of chickadees but not their actual survival.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Egan |first1=E.S. |last2=Brittingham |first2=M.C. |title=Winter Survival Rates of a Southern Population of Black-capped Chickadees |year=1994 |journal=Wilson Bulletin |volume=106 |issue=3| page=514}}</ref>

===Metabolism===
On cold winter nights, these birds can reduce their body temperature by as much as 12°C (from their normal temperature of about 42°C) to conserve energy.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Chaplin |first=S. B. |title=Daily energetics of the Black-capped Chickadee, ''Parus atricapillus'', in winter |journal=Journal of Comparative Physiology |doi=10.1007/BF00695350 |year=1974 |volume=89 |issue=4 |pages=321–330|bibcode=1974JCmPA..89..321C |s2cid=34190772 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Chaplin |first=S. B. |title=The physiology of hypothermia in the Black-capped Chickadee ''Parus atricapillus'' |journal=Journal of Comparative Physiology B |doi=10.1007/BF00692303 |year=1976 |volume=112 |issue=3 |pages=335–344|bibcode=1976JCmPB.112..335C |s2cid=31401778 }}</ref> Such a capacity for [[torpor]] is not very common in birds. Other bird species capable of torpor include the [[common swift]] (''Apus apus''), the [[common poor-will]] (''Phalaenoptilus nuttallii''), the [[lesser nighthawk]] (''Chordeiles acutipennis''), and various species of [[hummingbird]]s.<ref name="Hainsworth(1970)a">{{cite journal |last1=Hainsworth |first1=F. R. |last2=Wolf |first2=L. L. |title=Regulation of Oxygen Consumption and Body Temperature during Torpor in a Hummingbird, Eulampis jugularls |journal=Science |date=17 April 1970 |volume=168 |issue=3929 |pages=368–369 |doi=10.1126/science.168.3929.368 |pmid=5435893 |bibcode=1970Sci...168..368R |s2cid=30793291 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ruf |first1=Thomas |last2=Geiser |first2=Fritz |title=Daily torpor and hibernation in birds and mammals |journal=Biological Reviews |date=August 2015 |volume=90 |issue=3 |pages=891–926 |doi=10.1111/brv.12137 |pmid=25123049 |pmc=4351926 }}</ref>

===Movement and roosting===
During the winter, chickadees often [[Flocking (behavior)|flock]] together. Many other species of birds – including [[titmice]], [[nuthatches]], and [[New World warbler|warblers]] – can often be found foraging in these flocks. [[Mixed-species feeding flock|Mixed flocks]] stay together because the chickadees call out whenever they find a good source of food. This calling-out forms cohesion for the group, allowing the other birds to find food more efficiently.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Freeberg |first1=Todd M. |title=Chickadees, titmice and nuthatches flocking together benefit from a diversity bonus – so do other animals, including humans |url=https://theconversation.com/chickadees-titmice-and-nuthatches-flocking-together-benefit-from-a-diversity-bonus-so-do-other-animals-including-humans-192319 |website=[[The Conversation (website)|The Conversation]] |access-date=30 January 2024 |date=7 February 2023}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Thompson|first=Craig|date=Spring 1983|title=The dominance hierarchy of the Black-capped Chickadee and its relation to breeding territory and frequency of visitation to an artificial food source|url=http://dc.uwm.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1095&context=fieldstation_bulletins|journal=Field Station Bulletin|volume=16|pages=14–20|via=UWM Digital Commons}}</ref> Black-capped chickadees sleep in thick vegetation or in cavities, usually singly, though they may occasionally roost clumped together.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Loery |first1=G. |last2=Nichols |first2=J. D. |year=1985 |title=Dynamics of a Black-capped Chickadee population, 1958–1983 |journal=Ecology |volume=66 |issue=4 |pages=1195–1203 |jstor=1939172 |doi=10.2307/1939172|bibcode=1985Ecol...66.1195L }}</ref>

Their flight is slightly undulating with rapid wing beats. Flights are typically short bursts of less than {{cvt|15|m|ft|round=5}} with a speed around {{cvt|20|km/h}}.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Greenewalt |first=C. H. |year=1955 |title=The flight of the Black-capped Chickadee and the White-breated Nuthatch |journal=Auk |volume=72 |pages=1–5 |issue=1 |url=http://sora.unm.edu/node/20304 |doi=10.2307/4081384|jstor=4081384 |doi-access=free }}</ref> They tend to avoid flying through large open areas and will instead be found flying along tree-lines or through forests.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=St. Clair |first1=Colleen Cassady |last2=Bélisle |first2=Marc |last3=Desrochers |first3=André |last4=Hannon |first4=Susan |title=Winter Responses of Forest Birds to Habitat Corridors and Gaps |journal=Conservation Ecology |date=1998 |volume=2 |issue=2 |article-number=art13 |doi=10.5751/ES-00068-020213 |jstor=26271681 |bibcode=1998ConEc...2Tr.13S }}</ref>

===Moult===

Chickadees moult once a year, starting in July or August and usually taking two to three months. They do not moult in the spring prior to breeding. The postjuvenal moult at the end of the first summer of life is partial, involving only the body feathers and wing coverts. In subsequent years, the postnuptial moult at the end of each reproductive season is always complete, involving all feathers. Moulting chickadees are not often seen, preferring to remain silent and hidden from view.<ref name=Smith1991/>{{rp|167}}

===Dominance hierarchy===
During the winter, the species forms flocks through which dominance hierarchies can be easily observed. Dominance hierarchies play an important role in determining the social behaviours among the birds in these flocks. Chickadees with higher social rankings have better access to food during the winter, which leads to them having a better body condition, increased territory size, and higher reproductive success.<ref name="ReferenceA">{{cite journal |last1=An|first1=Yong Seok|last2=Kriengwatana|first2=Buddhamas|last3=Newman|first3=Amy E.|last4=Macdougall-Shackleton|first4=Elizabeth A.|last5=Macdougall-Shackleton|first5=Scott A.|title=Social Rank, Neophobia and Observational Learning in Black-capped Chickadees|journal=Behaviour|year=2011|volume=148|issue=1|pages=55–69|doi=10.1163/000579510x545829}}</ref><ref name=Smith1991/>{{rp|190–192}} The hierarchies are linear and stable; once a relationship is established between two birds, it stays the same for many years. In general, older and more experienced birds are dominant over younger ones, and males are dominant over females.<ref name="Kenneth A 2007"/> Dominant and subordinate members differ in their foraging strategies and risk-taking behaviours. Dominant individuals control access to preferred resources and restrict subordinates to foraging in novel, riskier, or suboptimal environments.<ref name=Smith1991/>{{rp|192–193}}
A 2011 study demonstrated that this results in subordinate individuals being less cautious approaching novel foods and objects compared to their dominant counterparts. This is similar to subordinate primates, which feed on novel food more readily than the dominant individuals because they are more used to eating suboptimal and unfamiliar food. No difference is observed in ability to learn novel foraging tasks between dominant and subordinate individuals.<ref name="ReferenceA" />

===Breeding===
[[File:Black-capped Chickadee (Poecile atricapillus) excavating a nest cavity in Waterville, Maine.jpg|thumb|A black-capped chickadee excavating a nest cavity in a dead tree]]

Black-capped chickadees start to form breeding pairs in the late fall and into the winter. In the spring, the winter flocks will disperse into the constituent pairs. They are largely [[Monogamy in animals|monogamous]] during this time, although occasionally males are observed mating with multiple females.<ref name=Smith1991/>{{rp|90–92}} Females prefer dominant males, and greater reproductive success is closely related to the higher ranking of the male.<ref name="Kenneth A 2007">{{cite journal |last1=Oort |first1=Harry Van |last2=Otter|first2=Kenneth A.|last3=Fort|first3=Kevin T.|last4=Mcdonell|first4=Zoe|title=Habitat, Dominance, And The Phenotypic Quality of Male Black-Capped Chickadees|journal=The Condor|year=2007 |volume=109|issue=1|page=88 |doi=10.1650/0010-5422(2007)109[88:hdatpq]2.0.co;2|s2cid=85729695 |doi-access=free}}</ref>

The black-capped chickadee nests in tree cavities {{cvt|1|-|7|m|ft|0}} above ground.<ref name=Smith1991/> The pair either excavates the hole together, uses a natural cavity, or reuses an old [[woodpecker]] nest. This species will also nest in a [[nest box]]. There are at least two cases where chickadees have reused an open cup nest of another species.<ref name=grooms>{{cite journal | last=Grooms | first =Chris | year=2025 | title=Black-capped Chickadee uses open-cup nest | journal=Ontario Birds | volume=43 | pages=150-153 }}</ref> Nest sites are typically chosen by females, but excavation of the cavity is done by both sexes. The nest itself is built by the female only and consists of a base of coarse material such as moss or bark strips, and lining of finer material such as mammal hair.<ref name="Aitken2007">{{cite journal |last1=Aitken |first1=Kathryn E. H. |last2=Martin |first2=Kathy |title=The importance of excavators in hole-nesting communities: availability and use of natural tree holes in old mixed forests of western Canada |journal=Journal of Ornithology |date=December 2007 |volume=148 |issue=S2 |pages=425–434 |doi=10.1007/s10336-007-0166-9 |s2cid=40674032 |url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10336-007-0166-9 |url-access=subscription }}</ref> The nesting season is from late April through June, with higher-ranking females nesting before lower ranking ones. Eggs are white, with fine reddish brown dots that are concentrated at the larger end. On average, eggs are {{cvt|1.52|x|1.22|cm|frac=16}}, and there are usually six to eight eggs. Incubation lasts 11–14 days and is by the female only; the male feeds her during this time.<ref name=Smith1991/> If an unusual disturbance occurs at the nest entrance, the incubating female may utter an explosive hiss like that of a snake, a probable adaptation to discourage nest predators.<ref>Forbush, E.H. (1925–29) Birds of Massachusetts and other New England states. Mass. Dept. of Agriculture, Boston.</ref>

[[File:Black capped chickadee hatchlings.jpg|thumb|right|Black-capped chickadee hatchlings are [[altricial]] and born without feathers.|alt=Two featherless black-capped chickadee hatchlings next to egg shells]]
Hatchlings are [[altricial]], emerging featherless with their eyes closed. Nestlings are fed by both sexes, but are brooded by the female only (the male brings food to her during brooding, which she passes on to the young). Young leave the nest 12–16 days after hatching, in great part because the parents start presenting food only outside the nest hole. The young are still fed by the parents for several weeks, but are capable of catching food on their own within a week after leaving the nest.<ref name=FooteBotW/>

Black-capped chickadees usually breed only once a year, but second broods are possible if the first one is lost. First breeding is at one year of age. Maximum recorded lifespan is 12 years,<ref>{{cite journal |last=Löf |first=R. A. |year=1967 |title=Ten years of banding black-capped chickadees |journal=EBBA News |volume=30 |pages=195–198}}</ref> although most live roughly 2.5 years.<ref name=FooteBotW/>

Black-capped chickadees may interbreed with [[Carolina chickadee|Carolina chickadees]] (''Poecile carolinensis'') or [[mountain chickadee]]s (''P. gambeli'') where their ranges overlap.<ref name="Martin1996">{{cite journal |last1=Martin |first1=Stephen G. |last2=Martin |first2=KathyAnne |title=Hybridization between a Mountain Chickadee and Black-capped Chickadee in Colorado |journal=C.F.O Journal |date=April 1996 |volume=30 |issue=2 |pages=60–65 |url=https://cobirds.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/CB_1996_30_2_April-1996.pdf#page=18 }}</ref><ref name="Bronson2005">{{cite journal |last1=Bronson |first1=C. L. |last2=Grubb |first2=Thomas C. |last3=Sattler |first3=Gene D. |last4=Braun |first4=Michael J. |title=Reproductive Success Across The Black-Capped Chickadee (''Poecile atricapillus'') and Carolina Chickadee (''P. carolinensis'') Hybrid Zone in Ohio |journal=The Auk |date=1 July 2005 |volume=122 |issue=3 |pages=759–772 |doi=10.1093/auk/122.3.759}}</ref> Interbreeding with [[boreal chickadee]]s (''P. hudsonicus'') has also been documented, though it is more rare.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lait |first1=Linda |last2=Lauff |first2=R. F. |last3=Burg |first3=T. M. |title=Genetic evidence supports Boreal Chickadee (''Poecile hudsonicus'') x Black-capped Chickadee (''Poecile atricapillus'') hybridization in Atlantic Canada |journal=The Canadian Field-Naturalist |year=2012 |volume=126 |page=143|doi=10.22621/cfn.v126i2.1330 |doi-access=free }}</ref>

===Predators and parasites===
Black-capped chickadees are primarily subject to predation by [[birds of prey]], including owls, hawks, and shrikes. Nest-predation also occurs, primarily by raccoons, squirrels, opossums, and snakes.<ref name=Smith1991/>{{rp|255–260}} Nest sites are also sometimes raided by [[Northern house wren|house wren]]s, who will destroy chickadee eggs to reuse the location for their nest.<ref name="Kluyver1961">{{cite journal |last1=Kluyver |first1=H. N. |title=Food Consumption in Relation to Habitat in Breeding Chickadees |journal=The Auk |date=October 1961 |volume=78 |issue=4 |pages=532–550 |doi=10.2307/4082187 |jstor=4082187 |hdl=20.500.11755/63e29ec0-8e43-4e71-99c6-f17eddd7fd4d |hdl-access=free }}</ref>

Like many birds, black-capped chickadees are susceptible to [[West Nile Virus|West Nile virus]]. They are also known to be affected by blood parasites, including those that cause [[malaria]], but particularly high rates of infection have not been detected.<ref name=FooteBotW/> Black-capped chickadees are also known to be affected by [[avian keratin disorder]].<ref name="VanHermert2012">{{cite journal |last1=Van Hemert |first1=Caroline |last2=Handel |first2=Colleen M. |last3=O'Hara |first3=Todd M. |title=Evidence of Accelerated Beak Growth Associated with Avian Keratin Disorder in Black-Capped Chickadees (''Poecile atricapillus'') |journal=Journal of Wildlife Diseases |date=July 2012 |volume=48 |issue=3 |pages=686–694 |doi=10.7589/0090-3558-48.3.686 |pmid=22740534 |bibcode=2012JWDis..48..686V |url=https://meridian.allenpress.com/jwd/article/48/3/686/121814/EVIDENCE-OF-ACCELERATED-BEAK-GROWTH-ASSOCIATED }}</ref>

==State and provincial bird==
[[File:Maine license plate.jpg|thumb|right|A Maine registration plate, with a black-capped chickadee on the left|alt=A vehicle registration plate from Maine, with a black-capped chickadee perched on a pine branch on the left of the plate]]

The black-capped chickadee is the [[List of U.S. state birds|state bird]] of Maine and Massachusetts and the [[List of Canadian provincial and territorial symbols|provincial bird]] of New Brunswick.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://bangordailynews.com/2019/02/28/news/state/a-nest-divided-maines-great-chickadee-debate/ | title= The problem with naming 'the chickadee' as Maine's state bird |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190307054318/https://bangordailynews.com/2019/02/28/news/state/a-nest-divided-maines-great-chickadee-debate/ |archive-date=7 March 2019 | publisher=[[Bangor Daily News]] |date= 28 February 2019 |access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.shgresources.com/ma/symbols/bird/ |title=Massachusetts State Bird|publisher=SHG Resources |access-date=3 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224034147/http://www.shgresources.com/ma/symbols/bird/ |archive-date=24 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=NB>{{cite web |url=http://www2.gnb.ca/content/gnb/en/departments/government_services/symbols.html |title=Symbols of New Brunswick |author=Government of New Brunswick |access-date=10 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170709060607/http://www2.gnb.ca/content/gnb/en/departments/government_services/symbols.html |archive-date=9 July 2017 }}</ref> In 2022 the black-capped chickadee was named the official bird of [[Calgary, Alberta]].<ref name="CalgaryBird">{{cite web |last1=Lirette |first1=Dominika |title=The votes are in. Calgary's official bird is... |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/calgary-vote-official-bird-chickadee-1.6453753 |website=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] |access-date=18 January 2024}}</ref> In 2015 the black-capped chickadee was voted the unofficial bird of [[Ottawa|Ottawa, Ontario]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=May 30, 2015 |title=Black-capped chickadee is your choice for Ottawa's unofficial bird |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/black-capped-chickadee-is-your-choice-for-ottawa-s-unofficial-bird-1.3054114 |access-date=March 21, 2025 |website=CBC News}}</ref> The bird is prominently featured on the standard Maine vehicle registration plate.<ref>{{cite web |title=Maine License Plates |url=https://www.maine.gov/sos/kids/government/license-plates |website=Maine.gov Kids |publisher=Maine Secretary of State |access-date=18 January 2024}}</ref>

==Conservation==
The [[IUCN]] classifies the black-capped chickadee as [[least-concern species|least concern]] due to its wide distribution and large populations. Yearly bird counts such as the [[Christmas Bird Count]] indicate that the population is increasing. The total population across its range is estimated to be 43 million mature individuals as of 2025.<ref name="iucn status" />

Black-capped chickadees are known to suffer from human-related mortality causes such as flying into windows or dying from ingesting pesticide. Additionally, pets such as [[Cat|cats]] pose a threat to chickadees.<ref name=Smith1991/>

